{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16290"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16290"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.76,0,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8981"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7494"},{"type":"tags","id":"8561"},{"type":"tags","id":"10447"},{"type":"tags","id":"10448"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22717"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inner ear contains a complex system of fluid-filled spaces that are essential for balance and hearing. There is a fluid distribution of perilymph and endolymph between the bony labyrinth and the membranous labyrinth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following fluid distributions is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bony labyrinth contains endolymph and membranous labyrinth contains perilymph","Bony labyrinth contains perilymph and membranous labyrinth contains endolymph","Both labyrinths contain endolymph","Both labyrinths contain mixture of perilymph and endolymph","Both labyrinths contain perilymph"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebony labyrinth contains perilymph while the membranous labyrinth contains endolymph\u003C/strong\u003E. This arrangement is crucial for inner ear function. The membranous labyrinth floats within the bony labyrinth, suspended in perilymph.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaving \u003Cstrong\u003Eboth structures containing endolymph\u003C/strong\u003E would not allow for proper ionic gradients needed for sensory function. Having \u003Cstrong\u003Eboth structures containing perilymph\u003C/strong\u003E would similarly disrupt sensory function. Having the \u003Cstrong\u003Ebony labyrinth contain endolymph and membranous labyrinth contain perilymph\u003C/strong\u003E is anatomically incorrect. Having a \u003Cstrong\u003Emixture of both fluids\u003C/strong\u003E would disrupt the precise ionic gradients needed for sensory function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerilymph is similar in composition to cerebrospinal fluid (high in sodium), while endolymph has a unique composition high in potassium. This difference in ionic composition is essential for proper function of the hair cells in the inner ear.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The bony labyrinth contains perilymph while the membranous labyrinth contains endolymph.","Perilymph is similar to cerebrospinal fluid while endolymph has a unique ionic composition high in potassium.","The membranous labyrinth floats within the bony labyrinth, separated by perilymphatic space."],"references":["Bahrani B, Khachemoune A. Review of accessory tragus with highlights of its associated syndromes. Int J Dermatol. 2014 Dec;53(12):1442-6. doi: 10.1111/ijd.12369. Epub 2014 Sep 30. PMID: 25266223","Heine PA. Anatomy of the ear. Vet Clin North Am Small Anim Pract. 2004 Mar;34(2):379-95. doi: 10.1016/j.cvsm.2003.10.003. PMID: 15062614","Szymanski A, Geiger Z. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Ear. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262017","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97946"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16290"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97946"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T16:58:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T17:00:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8981"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115947"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api